trategy kept customer acquisition costs exceptionally low: last year, they =
were less than $5 per customer.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
$5 is cool, but what if someone just gives you customers? TrueAccord=E2=80=
=99s main customers are companies that need to collect debts from customers=
 -- Yelp, Upwork, and LendUp are some of its clients -- and collectively, t=
hey send TrueAccord 500k - 1 million people per month. Yup, instead of payi=
ng to acquire customers, companies just send them to TrueAccord. Of those, =
5-30% choose to work with TrueAccord (it=E2=80=99s opt-in), and that number=
 is growing as TrueAccord=E2=80=99s positive reputation builds. People in d=
ebt are rational and want a way out, and TrueAccord is the friendliest, eas=
iest way to do that. Plus, the companies that send TrueAccord customers pay=
 it 15-20% of the money collected. So really, the consumer debt repayment p=
roduct that TrueAccord offers right now is a fast-growing, high-margin,=C2=
=A0 negative-CAC channel for its bigger ambitions.=C2=A0
Once TrueAccord owns the customer relationship and has helped those consume=
rs out of debt, it can begin to layer on additional financial services: par=
tnerships with neobanks, debit cards, banking services. These are excellent=
 businesses once the customer is in the door, but many attempts die at the =
hands of high CACs. TrueAccord is playing the long game, and has been for t=
he past seven years, because it knows it can do well by doing good.=C2=A0
Fewer consumers in debt, more consumers with access to financial services, =
more profits for TrueAccord.=C2=A0
It sounds like a perfect playbook. Why hasn=E2=80=99t anyone done it before=
?=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0
Unsexiness-as-a-Moat
We can all agree that debt collection isn=E2=80=99t sexy. We all want to av=
oid it entirely, and those of us who=E2=80=99ve had to engage know that it=
=E2=80=99s a terrible and hopeless experience.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s equally difficult to build a business in the space: there are =
compliance issues, reputational issues, people treat their vendors like shi=
t, it=E2=80=99s commoditized, and there=E2=80=99s fierce competition from b=
oiler room call centers. It=E2=80=99s different than traditional SaaS: your=
 clients don=E2=80=99t love you, there=E2=80=99s no customer obsession. The=
 best you can do is make sure that a customer=E2=80=99s experience with you=
 sucked less than the customer=E2=80=99s experience with another company.=
=C2=A0
For most people, that=E2=80=99s a deterrent. For Ohad, that was an opportun=
ity. He bet that people would be attracted to other, shinier opportunities =
in fintech and avoid getting their hands dirty in consumer debt collection.=
 He was right, and that=E2=80=99s given him and the TrueAccord team a seven=
 year head start.=C2=A0
That head start means it=E2=80=99s worked with more than 16 million consume=
rs, built up a massive database on what works with which types of vendors, =
and built something counterintuitive: a respected brand in debt collection.=
 After years, people are talking online about their relatively positive exp=
eriences with TrueAccord, and that helps convince others to work with them =
when their collections are handed over.=C2=A0
It also means that TrueAccord has been able to build a uniquely cohesive cu=
lture.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s something bonding,=E2=80=9D Ohad quipped, =E2=80=
=9Cabout a vision so compelling that smart people are willing to tell their=
 friends and families they work in debt collection.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The culture that TrueAccord has built around that vision is one of the comp=
any=E2=80=99s strengths and something that keeps it on the right track. He =
said that if he tried to ask TrueAccord=E2=80=99s head designer to do somet=
hing that started exploiting consumers now that they=E2=80=99re big enough =
to do so, =E2=80=9CShe would tell me to go to hell and then quit on the spo=
t. As she should.=E2=80=9D The company culture he described is like an anti=
body to bad behavior. =E2=80=9CWe don=E2=80=99t need a =E2=80=98no assholes=
=E2=80=99 rule here because an asshole would naturally feel so out of place=
=2E=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
TrueAccord is mission-driven, operating in an unsexy space, and taking a lo=
nger view than anyone in the room. It would be nearly impossible for a well=
-funded startup to come in and compete with TrueAccord because of the moat =
it=E2=80=99s built, and no large player wants the reputational risk of work=
ing in debt collection. It may be one of the few fintech companies impervio=
us to Stripe=E2=80=99s ever-expanding scope; can you imagine Stripe Collect=
?=C2=A0
What I Missed =C2=A0
In the past year, instead of turning its focus more directly on consumers, =
TrueAccord discovered an opportunity to reach even more customers by provid=
ing white-labeled early-stage collection services to fintech companies via =
Retain. The vision remains the same, but the sequencing is different. Retai=
n offers the opportunity to help the most people avoid default today.
That said, the same strategies apply to Retain:=C2=A0
Debt Collection as a Wedge. TrueAccord is using its experience, technology,=
 and reputation in debt collection to wedge into the stacks of a new genera=
tion of creditors instead of using debt collection as a wedge into offering=
 more financial services to the unbanked itself (for now).
Unsexiness as a Moat. Given the choice between extending someone a loan or =
trying to collect their debt, 99 out of 100 fintech companies would choose =
(and have chosen) the former. That means that there=E2=80=99s been an explo=
sion in the number of companies offering credit, but there hasn=E2=80=99t b=
een a commensurate explosion in the number of companies who can collect deb=
ts when it comes to it in a way that fintech companies would be proud to pa=
rtner with.=C2=A0
Those two strategies have afforded TrueAccord the rare opportunity to build=
 core infrastructure in a fast-growing space uncontested.=C2=A0
Embedded Finance, BNPL, and Retain
In a year of financial markets craziness, 2021 belonged to fintech. That me=
ant more new companies offering more credit products to more consumers.=C2=
=A0
In the private markets, according to CB Insights [https://email.mg2.substac=
k.com/c/eJxFkE9rhDAQxT_N5raSvxs95NAWCr320KtEM7rpaiLJWPHbN6uFwjDzmMfwmF9vEca=
YdrPEjOTZWtwXMAG2PAEiJLJmSK13ht14LZRsiDPSsVrVxOd2SACz9ZPBtAJZ1m7yvUUfw3FBKV=
fkbgS1wormBrIZNJMWNGW60cqKHmqg6sy1q_MQejDwA2mPAchk7ohLvoiXC38vtW1b1Xc-ZD_eM=
Vd9nMsywRIT5qLeXq8ff177BQHXBNfPw71yylm1uIF4UySngmnGFRe84tWtszAI6exQS3C6r8T6=
vQTr-EXSeeRVXruMtn8880gyIWIXkw9jsR93O8N0GOX1tsx5DR73FoLtJnAnFTzhHpzaEQKkAt2=
1FgtSqRVnSlNV65NCwaaobKjSkpRkF8tV-A_9BQP7koM], fintech companies accounted =
for $131 billion of the total $621 billion in global venture capital fundin=
g.=C2=A0
Within fintech, two of the biggest trends have been embedded finance and Bu=
y Now Pay Later (BNPL).=C2=A0
Embedded finance is a topic we=E2=80=99ve covered a few times in Not Boring=
, when we talked about Unit [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkN1uhCAQh=
Z9G7mpwgFUvuGjS7GsQkNGlq2D4qfHty65JmzBMMpMzJ-ebdMYlxFPuIWXy-lQ-d5Qej7RizhhJ=
SRiVs7K7wcAEH4mV3HaDGIhLao6Im3arzLEg2YtZ3aSzC_6toBQEeUikZkbOZ2OpNqMAqKds17G=
