YZ1alGNfcJaO40wjxowt433fGzR0B103JbVFOOqTD45_uSyDYmnlIOcanj5wM2Wj-DSuNq3Y4Y-=
HQUYVoJL1C-_Pqgu4Ui5eojOuDqku6Nak0vzdBfYNUJU_Gl6bWoypjqVvwX_QPSgoOC] define=
s it as, =E2=80=9CWhen a non-financial services company creates financial s=
ervices products for their users, embedding them into its existing products=
=2E=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
For purposes of today=E2=80=99s discussion, what it means is that more non-=
banks are extending credit to customers than ever before.=C2=A0
BNPL =E2=80=93 which essentially extends customers zero-interest loans at t=
he point-of-sale in order to increase conversion =E2=80=93 had an even bigg=
er year than embedded finance:=C2=A0
In January 2021, Affirm priced its IPO at $49 and popped 110% on its first =
day of trading to a market cap of $24 billion. It peaked at $46 billion in =
November.
In June, Softbank led a round in Ohad=E2=80=99s old company, Swedish BNPL K=
larna, that valued it at $46 billion.
In August, Square bought Aussie BNPL Afterpay for $29 billion.=C2=A0
Things have cooled off since from a valuation perspective. Affirm, whose bi=
ggest customer, Peloton, has struggled, is trading at around $8 billion. In=
dex Ventures=E2=80=99 Mark Goldberg pointed out that, because it=E2=80=99s =
still private and not marked daily, Klarna is on paper worth more than a ba=
sket of big public fintechs combined:=C2=A0
But for our discussion, what=E2=80=99s important is volume, not valuations.=
 A Juniper Research report [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkcuOhCAURL=
-m2WkQeeiCxWzmNwyPq80MAgFs498Pdi8mIdwbKpWqHIyqsMV8yRRLRfe11CuBDHAWD7VCRkeBv=
DgrB06mkdEZWUntMLEJubKsGWBXzsuaD0Dp0N4ZVV0MbwfGhKGnFGymGDAjBBsQfB2IEJyulBtO=
qRmnT646rINgQMIL8hUDIC-ftabyGL8e5Lud8zz7pK4dQi3WvaA3cW_Pd9c2dEi-KwmCdWHrauz=
KCd7fyzwz3W0-auX91emrI5jwrtTDXt3qgr3dHA8Tn9uCnGwyweMgBsLISHrSc61gHalV60TBCt=
OPx08KypIHxftG-nLoUpX5vQuhLEOsOubWosm_T7WDfwuNztLmfgRXrwWC0h7sB1z98H-jXDYIk=
Nu_2EXVRp0KRgYmMJvEB1QjyzCdMRMUtWQbmyv8h_4BgrScyA] estimated $226 billion i=
n 2021 BNPL volume, and projected growth to $995 billion by 2026, or roughl=
y 25% of all ecommerce spending. Once again, more non-banks are extending c=
redit to customers than ever before.=C2=A0
Both embedded finance and BNPL might want to offer credit to more people, b=
ut they don=E2=80=99t have the (old, shitty, harassing, etc=E2=80=A6) infra=
structure that banks have in place to make sure that they can prevent borro=
wers from defaulting and collect if they do. They=E2=80=99re faced with a f=
ew options:=C2=A0
Build. Fintech companies could build collections in-house, but it=E2=80=99s=
 complicated from a compliance perspective, not a core competency, and not =
sexy enough to excite employees. Plus, as discussed in last year=E2=80=99s =
memo, many companies don=E2=80=99t want collections on their hands.=C2=A0
Bad. They could go with the bad solutions =E2=80=93 working with traditiona=
l collection agencies who harass people and often end up in court =E2=80=93=
 but that would be bad for brand, wouldn=E2=80=99t integrate technologicall=
y, and could hurt morale and mission.=C2=A0
Partner with TrueAccord. TrueAccord has the expertise, experience, and tech=
nical chops to collect more effectively than traditional agencies, and it=
=E2=80=99s the only modern solution that modern companies don=E2=80=99t fee=
l weird turning their customers over to.
More and more, embedded finance and BNPL companies are turning to TrueAccor=
d and using one or both of its two products:=C2=A0
